export const postHtml = "<p><em>Working copy v7 (pre-publish pass done: numbers verified against RESULTS.md M3e\u2013M3g). Math is\n<code>$\u2026$</code>/display LaTeX for MDX+KaTeX. The tail notes and this line are stripped by the exporter.</em></p>\n<hr />\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>TL;DR.</strong> The benchmark-winning way of making an LLM \"think harder\" (particle filtering on\nprocess-reward scores) provably samples the wrong distribution, and in doing so destroys the\none signal that tells you when to distrust an answer, irreversibly by the time you can measure\nit. The mathematics that shows this is seventy years old, and it also supplies the fix: keep\n25% of the compute as a never-resampled insurance stratum, which costs no accuracy and restores\nthe signal. Proofs on an enumerable toy model, measurements on real runs, and an interactive\nreplay of the collapse are all below.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I have spent a good part of my PhD being professionally paranoid about samplers. In cosmology, when\nyou infer the composition of the universe from a map of gravitationally lensed galaxies, the answer\ncomes out of a sampler, an algorithm drawing from a posterior nobody can write in closed form. A\nsubtly wrong sampler produces no error message, only a slightly wrong universe with confidently\nnarrow error bars, and you can lose years to a \"cosmological tension\" that is actually a bug in\nsomeone's proposal distribution. So my field grew a culture around one paranoid question: <strong>is the\nsampler actually sampling the distribution it claims to?</strong> We have named tests for this\n(simulation-based calibration, coverage diagnostics), we run them routinely, and a posterior that\nhasn't passed them is treated as a rumor.</p>\n<p>Recently I aimed that paranoia at something far from my field, namely the methods that make a\nlanguage model \"think harder\" at inference time. I should be clear about what I am and am not\nhere: I am a cosmologist who knows samplers, physics, and uncertainty quantification, not an LLM\nresearcher, and I walked into the test-time-scaling literature the way a plumber walks into an\nunfamiliar house, with no opinions about the wallpaper and a professional interest in the pipes.\nWhat I found in the pipes is a benchmark-winning method that quietly destroys its own ability to\nknow when it is wrong, in a way the benchmark cannot see, and in a way that turns out to be\nirreversible by the time anyone looks. None of this has anything to\ndo with language. This post is about that finding, but it is mostly about the dictionary that made\nthe finding cheap: the mathematics on the two sides is the same mathematics, and once you write the\nmapping down, twenty years of sampler-audit reflexes transfer more or less mechanically.</p>\n<h2>The dictionary</h2>\n<p>The LLM setup, which I had to learn from scratch and will compress for anyone else arriving from\noutside: a generator writes math solutions step by step, a second model (a \"process reward model\", PRM) scores partial solutions for\npromise, and search methods use those scores to reallocate compute mid-generation. The benchmark\nwinner, as I write this in mid-2026, is particle filtering (Puri et al. 2025), which runs N attempts in parallel and at\nevery step kills the low-scoring ones and clones the high-scoring ones. Accuracy goes up, and the\npapers report the accuracy.</p>\n<p>Here is what that setup is, translated:</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>LLM inference</th>\n<th>what it is underneath</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>the base model $p(x_{1:T}) = \\prod_t p(x_t\\mid x_{&lt;t})$</td>\n<td>an autoregressive reference measure: you can sample it, you cannot renormalize it</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\"generate good solutions\"</td>\n<td>the tilted measure $\\sigma \\propto p\\,e^{r/\\beta}$, i.e. a Gibbs measure, i.e. a Bayesian posterior</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>the process reward model</td>\n<td>a learned value function, approximating the optimal \"twist\" $\\psi^\\star_t$</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>particle filtering over steps</td>\n<td>Feynman\u2013Kac sequential Monte Carlo</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>best-of-N</td>\n<td>the degenerate $T{=}1$ case of the same recursion</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p>None of these rows is an analogy. The tilted target is a Gibbs measure, the PRM is a value\nfunction, the filter is Feynman\u2013Kac, and I have worked with each of these objects under its other\nname, which is why the audit methodology transfers as machinery rather than as metaphor.</p>\n<p>So I did what my field trains you to do and stopped looking at the score, asking instead what\ndistribution the winning method actually samples.</p>\n<h2>The spine, in five equations</h2>\n<p>Everything below hangs on what probabilists call Feynman\u2013Kac structure, and the name deserves a\nshort digression, because its origin story is this post's thesis in miniature. Feynman's\npath-integral picture of quantum mechanics writes an amplitude as a sum over trajectories, each\nweighted by a factor accumulated along the way. Mark Kac noticed in 1949 that if you run Feynman's\nclock in imaginary time, the oscillating weights become decaying ones and the construction turns\ninto legitimate probability: an expectation over random walks, with every path multiplicatively\nreweighted by a potential collected step by step. That pairing of free dynamics with accumulated\nweights then kept surfacing everywhere. It computes ground states in quantum chemistry as\n\"diffusion Monte Carlo,\" it models selection acting on lineages in population genetics, and it\ntracks aircraft as the particle filter, until Del Moral's 2004 book proved these are all one\nobject and gave it the two physicists' names. A language model generating step by step under a\nreward model's scores is simply the newest instance: the base model supplies the dynamics and the\nPRM supplies the potential. The mathematics predates the transformer by seventy years and does not\ncare. (For the LLM instantiation see Zhao et al. 2024.)</p>\n<p>With the name earned, I will give each piece in its official form and then in words, because the\nwords are where the bug becomes visible.</p>\n<p>The target is the reward-tilt of the base model,</p>\n<p>$$\\sigma(x_{1:T}) \\;=\\; \\frac{1}{Z}\\, p(x_{1:T})\\, e^{r(x_{1:T})/\\beta},\n\\qquad Z = \\mathbb{E}_p\\!\\left[e^{r/\\beta}\\right].$$</p>\n<p>In words: take every solution the model could conceivably write, and reweight each one by how good\nits final answer is, with the temperature $\\beta$ setting how hard you lean. At large $\\beta$ you\nbarely touch the base model, at small $\\beta$ you pile everything onto the best answers, and in\nbetween you get a distribution that still remembers what a plausible solution looks like while\nfavoring the good ones. The normalizer $Z$ measures how much of the model's probability already\nsits on high-reward territory, which will matter in a moment. And $\\sigma$ is not an arbitrary\nchoice, because it is the unique solution of the KL-regularized control problem</p>\n<p>$$\\sigma = \\arg\\max_q \\left\\{ \\mathbb{E}_q[r] - \\beta\\, D_{\\mathrm{KL}}(q\\,\\|\\,p) \\right\\},$$</p>\n<p>that is, the best possible compromise between scoring high and staying plausible. Readers from the\nalignment world will recognize this as the RLHF objective. Preference training amortizes $\\sigma$\ninto weights while test-time search buys it with compute, so the two are the same target on\ndifferent payment plans.</p>\n<p>There is a structural problem, though: the model writes one token at a time, but the reward only\nexists at the end. The bridge between them is the optimal twist, the conditional expectation of\nthe terminal potential,</p>\n<p>$$\\psi^\\star_t(x_{1:t}) = \\mathbb{E}_{p(x_{t+1:T}\\mid x_{1:t})}\\!\\left[e^{r/\\beta}\\right],\n\\qquad\n\\psi^\\star_t = \\mathbb{E}_{p(x_{t+1}\\mid x_{1:t})}\\!\\left[\\psi^\\star_{t+1}\\right].$$</p>\n<p>In words, the twist answers the question a chess engine answers about a midgame position: not \"was\nthat move good\" but \"how do games passing through this position tend to end, averaged over the\nways the game might continue.\" It is a value function. The recursion on the right says that\ntoday's promise is the average of tomorrow's promise, which is the Bellman equation wearing\nsampling clothes. And this is the most useful line in the whole dictionary: <strong>a PRM is a learned\napproximation of $\\psi^\\star_t$.</strong> When a reward model scores a half-written solution, it is\nestimating an average over futures. The entire story turns on that fact.</p>\n<p>Given any twist $\\psi_t \\approx \\psi^\\star_t$, the proper sequential sampler weights particles by\nthe incremental ratio</p>\n<p>$$w_t = \\frac{\\psi_t(x_{1:t})}{\\psi_{t-1}(x_{&lt;t})}.$$</p>\n<p>The idea is to charge each step only for the <em>new</em> promise it added. A step that turns a mediocre\nprefix into a great one pays a large weight, while a step that merely preserves the promise its\nprefix already had pays nothing, because that promise was priced in at the previous step. Multiply\nthe ratios along a trajectory and everything interior cancels, so by the end each solution has\nbeen charged exactly once, for the quality of its final answer. That cancellation is what \"targets\n$\\sigma$\" means, mechanically. Two classical gifts come free. The normalizer estimate $\\hat Z =\n\\prod_t \\big(\\tfrac1N\\sum_i w_t^{(i)}\\big)$ is unbiased, and by Jensen the gap $\\log Z -\n\\mathbb{E}[\\log \\hat Z]$ equals the KL divergence from the sampler's law to the target. In words,\nthe sampler carries its own odometer, and the amount by which the odometer under-reads is exactly\nhow far the sampler is from the right distribution. A correctness certificate, built into the\nalgorithm, for anyone who cares to read it.</p>\n<p>The benchmark-winning method does something different. It overwrites the weight with the absolute\nscore, $w_t = \\psi_t$, and resamples every step, so the product no longer telescopes and the\npopulation targets</p>\n<p>$$\\sigma' \\;\\propto\\; p \\prod_{t=1}^{T} \\psi_t \\;=\\; \\sigma \\cdot \\prod_{t=1}^{T-1}\\psi_t .$$</p>\n<p>Here is the same thing without symbols. The PRM's score of a half-solution already contains the\nfuture, since \"this looks promising\" means \"this will probably end well.\" Resampling on the\nabsolute score at every step therefore charges the population for the same future again and again,\nthe way a billing department might charge you the full annual subscription every month. No single\ncharge looks wrong, nothing crashes, and that is exactly why the bug is invisible from inside. (As\na sanity check, at $T=1$ there is only one charge, $\\sigma'=\\sigma$, and the bias vanishes, which\nis why best-of-N is innocent. That fact will matter again later.) On a 125-sequence toy model\nwhere all of this reduces to finite sums, the overcharge comes out to 0.20 nats with the <em>optimal</em>\ntwist, so the scheme is off target even when the reward model is perfect, which tells you the\nproblem is the scheme.</p>\n<h2>The sampler runs colder than you asked</h2>\n<p>What kind of \"off\" is $\\sigma'$? Fit an effective temperature: find the $\\gamma^\\star$ minimizing\n$D_{\\mathrm{KL}}\\!\\big(\\sigma' \\,\\|\\, \\sigma_\\gamma\\big)$ over $\\sigma_\\gamma \\propto p\\,e^{\\gamma\nr/\\beta}$. On the toy model, exactly:</p>\n<p>$$\\gamma^\\star(T) = 1.45,\\; 1.80,\\; 2.00,\\; 2.20,\\; 2.35 \\quad \\text{for } T = 2,\\dots,6 .$$</p>\n<p>You set the temperature, but the sampler turns the thermostat down another notch with every\nselection round, and the fit is imperfect in an instructive way, since only about 60% of the\ndivergence is temperature-like and no amount of post-hoc rescaling recovers $\\sigma$ either.</p>\n<p><img alt=\"The depth law: effective over-tilt grows roughly linearly with resampling rounds (exact)\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig3_depthlaw.png\" /></p>\n<p>Cold systems concentrate, and the over-cooled sampler collects a little extra reward (mild\nGoodhart, which the benchmark dutifully rewards) while its answer distribution collapses toward\nunanimity. That collapse is a calibration catastrophe. Measured on hard MATH problems, across\nseeds, across budgets $N\\in\\{8,16,32\\}$, and across two models, the winning method reports around\n99% population confidence at 65 to 70% accuracy, and its confidence cannot rank its right answers\nabove its wrong ones (AUROC $0.51 \\pm 0.02$, which is a coin flip). The identical statistic under\nplain independent sampling is the standard self-consistency confidence, and it works fine there,\nwith an AUROC around 0.8. The search did not so much miscalibrate the signal as delete it.</p>\n<p>Two follow-ups sharpen the point. First, the method's own authors published a diversity-preserving\npatch (ePF, entropic annealing), built precisely to fight this collapse. We ran it, and it recovers\nthe reward as advertised while restoring none of the signal, with the same collapsed entropy and\nthe same dead AUROC. The patch fixes the symptom its authors were optimizing for, which is fair\nenough, but as far as I can find, nobody checked the distribution. Second, on a general-purpose model, where the search\ngenuinely buys 13.5 extra points of accuracy over best-of-N, the signal dies exactly the same way. So\nthis is not a no-free-lunch story but a specific bill, itemized to a line of the menu that nobody\nreads.</p>\n<p><img alt=\"The collapse, and the published patch does not restore the signal (3 seeds, N=16)\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig4_reliability.png\" /></p>\n<p><img alt=\"Accuracy vs confidence-AUROC, the axis the leaderboard does not print\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig1_money.png\" /></p>\n<p>The structural point, stated once: benchmarks are functionals of the argmax while the damage lives\nin the measure, so an accuracy-shaped scoreboard cannot price the damage, and worse, its gradient\npoints toward the methods that incur it.</p>\n<h2>Interlude: do we even care about calibration in LLMs?</h2>\n<p>Fair question, and I want to steelman it before answering, because the answer people usually give\n(\"the literature says calibration matters\") convinces nobody. LLMs are mostly used as argmax\nmachines, where the user takes the top answer and applies their own judgment, and nobody inspects a\npopulation confidence. On top of that, \"calibration\" carries a whiff of metric ghetto, a number\noptimized by people who publish about that number. If your use case is one-shot answers read by a\nskeptical human, you genuinely don't care, and the over-cooled sampler is even mildly good for you,\nsince its greed buys those few extra points of accuracy.</p>\n<p>The real argument has two steps. <strong>Step one is a distinction.</strong> \"Calibration\" conflates two\nproperties. One is <em>scale</em>, asking whether the system is right 90% of the time when it says 90%.\nScale errors are cheap to fix after the fact (temperature scaling, Platt) because they are a\nmonotone relabeling of an intact signal. The other is <em>rank</em>, asking whether higher confidence\nactually means more likely right. Rank is measured by AUROC, and rank damage is not fixable\nafterwards, because no monotone map creates information that isn't there. What the search destroys\nis rank, so the standard dismissal (\"who cares, just recalibrate\") fails on the same one-way-door\nlogic as everything else in this post: there is nothing left to recalibrate.</p>\n<p><strong>Step two is why rank is where the money is.</strong> Any deployment that is not a human reading one\nanswer contains a decision with asymmetric costs, whether that is answering now versus escalating\nto a bigger model, acting versus verifying first, or auto-accepting versus routing to a person. The\noptimal policy for every one of these is a threshold on a confidence score, which means the entire\nvalue of the system is a function of that score's rank quality. At AUROC 0.5 no useful threshold\nexists, your options collapse to verifying everything (no automation left) or accepting the full\nerror rate (silent corruption), and the middle ground where deployment actually lives is gone.</p>\n<p>Concretely, with our own numbers, on the same 280 problems with the same particle budget and two\nsamplers: play the escalation game, where you may send the fraction $q$ of answers the system is\nleast confident about to an oracle (a stronger model, a human, a verifier) that always gets them\nright.</p>\n<table>\n<thead>\n<tr>\n<th>check budget $q$</th>\n<th>search-based winner (acc 67%, AUROC 0.51)</th>\n<th>diversity-preserving (acc 61%, AUROC 0.82)</th>\n</tr>\n</thead>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>0%</td>\n<td><strong>67.1%</strong></td>\n<td>61.1%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>10%</td>\n<td><strong>72.9%</strong></td>\n<td>68.9%</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>20%</td>\n<td>76.0%</td>\n<td><strong>77.1%</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>30%</td>\n<td>78.9%</td>\n<td><strong>84.6%</strong></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>50%</td>\n<td>85.0%</td>\n<td><strong>91.1%</strong></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n<p><img alt=\"The escalation game: the method ordering inverts at a 20% verification budget\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig2_escalation.png\" /></p>\n<p>The benchmark winner starts six points ahead, and that opening row is the leaderboard row, the only\nrow a benchmark prints. Give the system any realistic verification budget and the ordering inverts:\nby $q=20\\%$ the \"less accurate but honest\" sampler has overtaken it, and at 30% it leads by almost\nsix points, because its confidence concentrates twice as many of its errors into the checked pile\n(41% versus 27% of all errors in the bottom-20% bucket). The two systems solve the same task with\nthe same compute, and their ranking flips the moment they are embedded in any larger process, which\nin practice means the moment they are deployed.</p>\n<p>There is also a version of this that lands close to irony. The premise of the entire test-time\nscaling field is adaptive compute, the idea that easy problems shouldn't cost what hard problems\ncost, and so something has to tell you, per problem, whether to stop or spend more. That something\nis the population's uncertainty, which makes it the fuel gauge of the whole enterprise. With the\nhonest sampler, the dumbest policy I could write (run $N{=}8$, escalate to $N{=}32$ only when\nconfidence is below 0.9) reaches the full flat-$N{=}32$ accuracy at an average of 25 particles\ninstead of 40, so the gauge alone is worth a 37% compute discount. Run the same policy on the\nbenchmark winner and it escalates 4% of problems, because its gauge is pinned at \"full\" everywhere,\nand it finishes <em>below its own flat $N{=}8$ accuracy</em>. Aggressive search saws off the branch that\nadaptive test-time scaling sits on: it always looks done, so it can never tell you where the next\nparticle should go.</p>\n<p>The quieter version, for anyone who runs models inside pipelines, is that a component whose outputs\ncarry no trustworthy uncertainty is what an emulator without error bars is in cosmology, unusable\nat any mean accuracy because you can neither check everything nor check nothing. And notice what\nthe collapsed population physically is: N samples you paid full compute for, reduced to N\nnear-copies of one guess. The uncertainty representation was the thing you were buying with the\nparallelism, and the search spent it on greed. (The training-time version of the same tilt, RLVR,\namortizes that trade into the weights, which is part of why reasoning models volunteer \"I'm not\nsure\" about as often as a student volunteers that the exam went badly.)</p>\n<h2>You can't unburn the toast</h2>\n<p>My first instinct was the one every importance-sampling person has, which is to reweight, because\nwe are a hammer-rich community. The sampler is off target, fine, but we logged every score it ever\nused, and the correction is a function of the surviving sequence alone:</p>\n<p>$$\\frac{d\\sigma}{d\\sigma'}(x) \\;\\propto\\; \\prod_{t=1}^{T-1}\\psi_t(x_{1:t})^{-1}.$$</p>\n<p>In words, it refunds the double-billed months: divide out every interior charge in one stroke.\nThe correction is computable from the logs with no new generation, and it is algebraically exact,\nunit-tested by feeding it true samples of $\\sigma'$ and watching it recover $\\sigma$ on the nose.</p>\n<p>On real logged runs it fails completely, and the reason it fails is the most transferable thing in\nthis project. Any reweighting is bounded by what survived,</p>\n<p>$$\\mathrm{TV}\\big(\\text{any reweighting},\\, \\sigma\\big) \\;\\ge\\; 1 - \\sigma(\\mathrm{supp}),$$</p>\n<p>which says nothing more mysterious than that no reweighting can conjure up answers that no\nsurviving particle is holding. And after a dozen winner-take-all rounds the surviving support\ncarries a few percent of $\\sigma$'s mass. On the exact toy the corrected estimator lands right on this floor, and on 400 logged\nproduction runs the final population typically descends from two or three of the thirty-two\nstarting lineages, which makes it the most confident committee I have ever seen in which everyone\nis a cousin. <strong>Selection does not distort the information, it destroys it.</strong> Population genetics\nhas owned this mathematics for a century under the name of genealogical coalescence, and the\neveryday version is familiar too: no weighting of the people you hired reconstructs the applicant\npool.</p>\n<p>Two warning lights fall out of the analysis, both computable from logs while the search runs. The\nESS of the would-be correction weights catches density distortion, which is the repairable kind,\nand the count of distinct ancestral lineages catches support destruction, which is not. The\nsubtlety I did not predict, and the detail I would most want an expert to remember, is that on\ncollapsed populations the weight-based light stays green, because the survivors are near-copies\nwhose weights agree, while the family tree underneath is quietly becoming a stump. Watch only the\nweights and the toast burns with the smoke detector saying \"all clear.\"</p>\n<div class=\"viz-embed\">\n<iframe src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/viz/\" title=\"trace replay: watch a particle filter's family tree collapse\"\n loading=\"lazy\"></iframe>\n<p class=\"viz-note\">Live replay of real logged runs. Drag the step slider, switch the particle\nbudget, hover a particle to trace its ancestry.\n<a href=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/viz/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Open it full-screen.</a></p>\n</div>\n<p><img alt=\"Forensics on 400 logged runs: the family tree collapses, and repair does not help\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig5_witness.png\" /></p>\n<h2>The fix is from 1995: buy insurance</h2>\n<p>If repair-after is impossible, the protection has to happen during the run. Split the budget so\nthat $(1-\\alpha)N$ particles run the aggressive search untouched while $\\alpha N$ form an insurance\nstratum that selection never touches, then take answers from the union, so the search keeps its\naccuracy, and take confidence from the insurance alone, which the search cannot corrupt. This is\ndefensive importance sampling, old enough to have grandchildren (Hesterberg 1995, Owen and Zhou\n2000). With the mixture proposal $q_\\alpha = \\alpha\\, p + (1-\\alpha)\\, q_{\\mathrm{search}}$ the\nweights are bounded,</p>\n<p>$$w(x) = \\frac{\\tilde\\sigma(x)}{q_\\alpha(x)} \\;\\le\\; \\frac{\\tilde\\sigma(x)}{\\alpha\\, p(x)},$$</p>\n<p>so the confidence estimator stays consistent with finite variance no matter how pathological the\nsearch stratum becomes. In words, because the insurance stratum guarantees every region of answer\nspace a minimum chance of being seen, no single sample can ever matter more than $1/\\alpha$ times\nits fair share, and that bound is what the guarantee is made of. Cosmology runs the same reflex in different clothes, since nobody in my\nfield estimates a correlation function without dragging a catalog of unclustered random points\nthrough the identical pipeline. We carry bags of random points around the way other people carry\numbrellas, and it looks exactly as silly, right up until it saves you.</p>\n<p>Measured at $\\alpha = 0.25$ on the real task, the design scores 68.0% against the full-budget\nsearch's 68.0%, so the insurance premium costs the selection nothing, to the decimal. Meanwhile the\ncalibration error drops by half (ECE 0.14 versus 0.25 to 0.33) and the AUROC comes back from the\ndead, from 0.53 to 0.70. The accuracy-or-trustworthiness trade-off the benchmark hides is not a law\nof nature but a design choice with a known premium, and the premium turns out to be small.</p>\n<p><img alt=\"The insurance design: the search's accuracy, the honest sampler's confidence\" src=\"/blog/sampling-is-sampling/fig6_defensive.png\" /></p>\n<h2>A note for the distribution-free crowd</h2>\n<p>If your reflex at this point is conformal prediction, meaning wrap the confidence in a\ndistribution-free guarantee and stop worrying about what the sampler did, the finding has an edge\nfor you too. Conformal methods are valid unconditionally, which is their glory, but their\n<em>efficiency</em>, the set sizes and the selective throughput, is entirely a function of the score's\nrank quality, and validity without efficiency certifies nothing you can use. On our tables,\ncalibrating a split-conformal selective policy (\"answer only above a threshold chosen so selected\nanswers are at least 80% correct\") gives the honest sampler a policy that answers 60% of problems\nat a realized 79%, so the guarantee transfers. On the collapsed sampler the target is unreachable\non 92% of calibration splits, because no threshold exists whose bucket clears 80% when the method's\nmost-confident answers are only about 68% correct. The wrapper stays valid, but the policy it\ncertifies is to abstain on essentially everything. Conformal prediction certifies whatever\ninformation survives the sampler, and it cannot manufacture information the sampler destroyed,\nwhich is this post's only real theme in one more costume. (The natural pairing, for what it's\nworth, is to conformalize <em>on the insurance stratum</em>, which is exactly the exchangeable,\nselection-untouched sample a conformal guarantee wants to see. The continuous version of all this,\nconformalized quantile regression on functionals of steered samplers, belongs to Part 2.)</p>\n<h2>The principles, without the LLMs</h2>\n<p>Strip the language models away and the project defends three statements about any system that\nsamples under selection:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><strong>Point-estimate scoreboards select for distributional damage.</strong> If the metric is a functional\n   of the argmax and tilting is free, over-tilting is rewarded, and the loss is booked to every\n   downstream consumer of the distribution, on a line the benchmark doesn't print.</li>\n<li><strong>Selection burns evidence at a compounding, quantifiable rate.</strong> Each round adds a notch of\n   effective coldness while the genealogy coalesces toward a stump, and past a witness-detectable\n   point no reweighting recovers the target, so the audit has to happen during the run, because\n   afterwards is arithmetic on ashes.</li>\n<li><strong>The untilted control sample is not optional.</strong> A small stratum kept outside the selection\n   process is what preserves a system's ability to know when it's wrong, and at least here it came\n   free.</li>\n</ol>\n<p>None of this is new mathematics, which is exactly the point. It comes from statistical mechanics,\npopulation genetics, and survey methodology, fields that live and die by stochastic simulators and\nthat spent decades building the distributional reliability practice LLM inference is currently\nrediscovering one silent failure at a time. The translation is not a metaphor but a short table and\nthe will to take it literally.</p>\n<h2>Honest boundaries</h2>\n<p>Everything here is one generator family (Qwen2.5, math-tuned and general variants), one PRM,\nMATH-500 level 4 and 5 (plus AIME at small n), and N up to 32, so it is a worked example rather\nthan a survey. The exact statements (wrong target, depth law, repair floor) live on an enumerable\ntoy, because that is where ground truth exists, and every real-task claim is a label-based\nmeasurement chosen to need no ground-truth posterior. The insurance design's AUROC recovers to\nabout 0.70 rather than the 0.75-plus of fully diversity-preserving sampling, since a four-particle\nstratum quantizes the confidence. And the deepest limitation motivates the sequel: on language\ntasks there is no exact posterior anywhere, so verification ultimately leans on the toy. The\nnatural home for this style of audit is a substrate where ground truth is computable at scale. I\nhappen to work with such substrates every day. They are called physical simulators, and that is\nPart 2.</p>\n<p>One more boundary concerns the author. I am not an LLM researcher, and it is entirely possible\nthat parts of this post read naively to people who live in that literature, in which case I would\ngenuinely like to hear where. The bet this post makes is narrower than expertise: it is only that\nthe sampler mathematics does not care which field it runs in.</p>\n<p><em>Code, logged runs, the interactive replay, and every number in this post: <a href=\"https://github.com/AndreasTersenov/particle-reasoners\">github.com/AndreasTersenov/particle-reasoners</a>. Machinery:\nDel Moral (2004), Zhao, Brekelmans, Makhzani and Grosse (2024), Talts et al. (2018), Lemos et al.\n(2023), Hesterberg (1995), Owen and Zhou (2000), Puri et al. (2025), Giannone et al. (2025, ePF).</em></p>\n<hr />";
